# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: headless-cms
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] In software development, **front end** refers to the presentation layer that users interact with, while **back end** refers to the data management and processing behind the scenes.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] In the client–server model, the client is usually considered the front end, handling most user-facing tasks, and the server is the back end, mainly managing data and logic.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] In software architecture, there can be many layers between the hardware and end user.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] The *front end* is an abstraction, simplifying the underlying components by providing a user-friendly interface, while the *back end* handles data storage and business logic.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] In telecommunication, the front end can be considered a device or service, while the back end is the infrastructure that supports the provision of services.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] A rule of thumb is that the front end, or client side, includes any components manipulated by the user.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] The back end, or server side, usually resides on the server, often far removed physically from the user.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] There are many different ways the terms 'front end' and 'back end' can be defined in the context of software.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] For example, in content management systems, the front end refers to views facing end users, and the back end refers to views facing administrative users.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] Similarly, within the field of speech synthesis, the front end refers to the part of the synthesis system that converts the input text into a symbolic phonetic representation, and the back end converts the symbolic phonetic representation into actual sounds.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] In programming language compilers, the front end translates computer source code into an intermediate representation, and the back end produces executable code from the intermediate representation.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] The back end usually optimizes to produce code that runs faster.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] The front end/back end distinction can also separate a parser that deals with source code from a compiler that generates and optimizes executable code.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] Some designs, such as GCC, offer multiple front end options (parsing different source languages) and multiple back end options (generating code for different target processors).
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] Some graphical user interface (GUI) applications act as a thin front end for underlying command-line interface (CLI) programs, to save users from having to learn the CLI terminology and commands.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] Another way to understand the differences between the front end and back end is to consider the knowledge that each requires of a software developer.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] The example lists below focus on web development.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] The front end communicates with the back end through an API.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] In the case of web and mobile front ends, the API is often based on HTTP requests/responses.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] An API can also reduce the front-end processing load by using different back-end services for different front-end interfaces, such as in the "Back end For Front end" (BFF) pattern.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] In computer networking, *front end* can refer to hardware that connects devices to the network, provides security such as a DMZ, or converts data into a transportable format.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] *Back end* refers to hardware that handles and transports data within the network.
[src:headless-cms/front-and-back-ends] In processor design, *front-end design* can refer to the initial description of a circuit's behavior in a hardware description language such as Verilog, while *back-end design* can refer to the process of mapping that behavior to physical transistors on a die.
[src:headless-cms/headless-content-management-system] A **headless content management system**, or **headless CMS**, is a back end-only web content management system that acts primarily as a content repository.
[src:headless-cms/headless-content-management-system] A headless CMS makes content accessible via an API for display on any device, without a built-in front end or presentation layer.
[src:headless-cms/headless-content-management-system] Cloud-first headless CMSes are those that were also built with a multi-tenant cloud model at their core and whose vendors promote software as a service (SaaS).
[src:headless-cms/headless-content-management-system] These vendors promise high availability, scalability, and full management of security, upgrades, and hotfixes on behalf of clients.
[src:headless-cms/headless-content-management-system] Headless commerce uses the same setup to separate back-end product management and navigation from the front end of a website or other display types (e.g., IoT).
[src:headless-cms/headless-content-management-system] This is similar to how headless CMS's focus on creating content in the back end to be displayed on front ends via APIs.
[src:headless-cms/headless-content-management-system] Headless CMS is similar to but distinct from the use of widgets or plugins on a site, like adding an online ordering and delivery plugin to a restaurant website.
[src:headless-cms/headless-content-management-system] Most monolithic content management systems are "coupled", meaning that the content management application (CMA) and the content delivery application (CDA) come together in a single application.
[src:headless-cms/headless-content-management-system] This makes back-end user tools, content editing and taxonomy, website design, and templates inseparable.
[src:headless-cms/headless-content-management-system] A decoupled CMS and a headless CMS have a lot in common as a headless CMS is a *type* of decoupled architecture.
[src:headless-cms/headless-content-management-system] The decoupled architecture allows for easier scalability and provides better security than coupled architecture, but it does not provide the same support for omnichannel delivery.
[src:headless-cms/headless-content-management-system] There are multiple environments to manage, hiking up infrastructure and maintenance costs.
[src:headless-cms/headless-content-management-system] The headless approach has also been applied to enterprise software outside of content management.
[src:headless-cms/headless-content-management-system] Example of this include Salesforce, who introduced Headless 360 following their acquisition of Contentful, decoupling its CRM platform from its proprietary interface and making the underlying data accessible via API to external tools and AI.
[src:headless-cms/headless-content-management-system] Headless CMS is a content management system (CMS) without a pre-built front-end presentation layer or templating system; instead, it provides a content repository and an API for managing the content.
[src:headless-cms/headless-content-management-system] While this allows for greater flexibility and customizability, it can also present challenges or drawbacks for teams and organizations.
[src:headless-cms/headless-content-management-system] The main downside is that it may require more effort to set up and configure and a certain level of web development knowledge on both the front and back end.
[src:headless-cms/jamstack] In JAMstack websites, the application logic typically resides on the client side (for example, an embedded e-commerce checkout service that interacts with pre-rendered static content), without being tightly coupled to a backend server.
[src:headless-cms/jamstack] JAMstack sites are usually served with a Git-based or headless CMS.
[src:headless-cms/static-site-generator] SSGs typically consist of a template written in HTML with a templating system, such as Liquid (Jekyll) or Go template (Hugo).
[src:headless-cms/static-site-generator] The same structure (typically a Git repository) includes content in a plain-text format such as Markdown or reStructuredText, or in a structural meta format such as JSON or XML.
[src:headless-cms/static-site-generator] A single plain-text file may correspond to a single web page.
[src:headless-cms/static-site-generator] Alternatively, a single structural metadata file may correspond to an entire website if a single-page application framework like AngularJS is used.
[src:headless-cms/static-site-generator] The website variable settings are stored in a plaintext configuration file `_config.yml` (YAML), `_config.toml` (TOML) or `_config.json` (JSON).
[src:headless-cms/static-site-generator] Page files typically also start with a YAML, TOML, or JSON preamble to define variables such as title, permalink, or date.
[src:headless-cms/static-site-generator] Files with names that begin with an underscore (`_`) such as `_index.md` (as opposed to `index.md`) are considered templates or archetypes and are thus not rendered as pages themselves.
[src:headless-cms/static-site-generator] Several hundred SSGs have been documented to exist, with the vast majority being written in languages that are already prominent on the web, such as Python, Go, JavaScript and TypeScript.
[src:headless-cms/static-site-generator] Many *server-side template systems* have the option to publish output pages on the server, where the published pages are static.
[src:headless-cms/static-site-generator] This is common on content management systems, like Vignette, but is not considered out-server generation.
[src:headless-cms/static-site-generator] In the majority of cases, this "publish option" doesn't interfere with the *template system*, and it can be made by external software, as Wget.
[src:headless-cms/static-site-generator] People began to use server-side dynamic pages generated from templates with pre-existing software adapted for this task.
[src:headless-cms/static-site-generator] This early software was the preprocessors and macro languages, adapted for web use, running on CGI.
[src:headless-cms/static-site-generator] Next, a simple but relevant technology was the direct execution made on extension modules, starting with SSI.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] A **web template system** in web publishing allows web designers and developers to work with *web templates* to automatically generate custom web pages, such as the results from a search.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] This reuses static web page elements while defining dynamic elements based on web request parameters.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] Web templates support static content, providing basic structure and appearance.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] Developers can implement templates from content management systems, web application frameworks, and HTML editors.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] The template and content resources are processed and combined by the template engine to mass-produce web documents, each with a similar visual format.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] For purposes of this article, web documents include any of various output formats for transmission over the web via HTTP, HTTPS, or another Internet protocol.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] A template processor (also known as a template engine or template parser) is software designed to combine *template*s with data (defined by a data model) to produce resulting documents or programs.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] The language that the templates are written in is known as a template language or templating language.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] For purposes of this article, a result document is any kind of formatted output, including documents, web pages, or source code (in source code generation), either in whole or in fragments.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] A template engine is ordinarily included as a part of a web template system or application framework, and may be used also as a preprocessor or filter.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] With the model typically held in a relational database, the remaining components of the MVC architecture are the control and view.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] In the simplest of systems these two are not separated.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] However, adapting the separation of concerns principle one can completely decouple the relationships.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] A web browser and web server are a client–server architecture.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] Sites often also use a web cache to improve performance.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] In many implementations, template files contain variables or placeholders that are replaced with data supplied by an application when the page is generated.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] The source code of the template engine can be proprietary or open source.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] Many template systems are a component of a larger programming platform or framework.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] They are referred to as the "platform's template system".
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] Some template systems have the option of substituting a different template language or engine.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] Programming languages such as Perl, Ruby, C, and Java support template processing either natively, or through add-on libraries and modules.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] JavaServer Pages (JSP), PHP, and Active Server Pages (ASP with VBScript, JScript or other languages) are examples, themselves, of web template engines.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] These technologies are typically used in server-side templating systems, but could be adapted for use on an "edge-side" proxy or for static page generation.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] Static site generators are engines that use flat text input files like markdown and asciidoc to generate a static web page.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] Examples of this include Jekyll (Liquid, Ruby), Hugo (Go templates), and Pelican (Jinja2, Python).
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] Some hosted website builders, including Wix, Weebly, and Duda, provide template-based systems that allow users to create static and dynamic web pages through graphical user interfaces rather than traditional programming.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] HTML editors often use web template systems to produce only static web pages.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] These can be viewed as a ready-made web design, used to mass-produce "cookie-cutter" websites for rapid deployment.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] They also commonly include themes in place of CSS styles.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] In general, the template language is used only with the editor's software.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] FrontPage and Dreamweaver were once the most popular editors with template sub-systems.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] A Flash web template uses Macromedia Flash to create visually interactive sites.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] Many *server-side template systems* have an option to publish output pages on the server, where the published pages are static.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] People began to use server-side dynamic pages generated from templates with pre-existent software adapted for this task.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] This early software was the preprocessors and macro languages, adapted for the web use, running on CGI.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] Next, a simple but relevant technology was the direct execution made on extension modules, started with SSI.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] Technically, the methodology of embedding programming languages within HTML (or XML, etc.), used in many "server-side included script languages" are also templates.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] All of them are Embedded complex languages.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] There are also preprocessors used as server-side template engines.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] As for edge-side template and inclusion systems, "edge-side" refers to web servers that reside in the space between the client (browser) and the originating server.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] They are often referred to as "reverse-proxy" servers.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] These servers are generally tasked with reducing the load and traffic on originating servers by caching content such as images and page fragments, and delivering this to the browser in an efficient manner.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] Basic Edge Side Includes (ESI) is an SSI-like language.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] ESI has been implemented for content delivery networks.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] The ESI template language may also be implemented in web browsers using JavaScript and Ajax, or via a browser "plug-in".
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] Many web browsers can apply an XSLT stylesheet to XML data that transforms the data into an XHTML document, thereby providing template functionality in the browser itself.
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] The most simple form is transclusions (HTML frames).
[src:headless-cms/web-template-system] In other cases dynamic web pages are needed.
